</rich_text><rich_text>• Ionic bonds are held together by the attraction of oppositely charged atoms. 
• Covalent bonds are formed when two atoms share a bond.
• Metallic bonds are formed when electrons can freely move throughout a metallic substance.
• The Lewis symbol shows an element and its valence electons (example for neon) :
  ..
 :Ne:
  ''
• The number of valence electrons in any main-group element is the same as that element's group number.
• The octet rule states that atoms tend to gain, lose, or share electrons until they have 8 valence electrons.
• Ionic substances are normally created from reactions of metals on the left with some on the right.</rich_text></node><node name="8.2" prog_lang="custom-colors" readonly="False" tags="School" unique_id="12"><rich_text underline="single">Section 8.2</rich_text><rich_text>
• Ionic substances are mostly stable due to mutual attraction.
• Lattice energy is the amount of energy required to completely separate one mole of a solid ionic compound into its gaseous ions.
• It is very difficult for electrons in the inner shells to be removed
• Many nonmetallic elements have ions that are noble-gas configurations
• Transition metals rarely have ions that have noble-gas configurations </rich_text></node></node></node><node name="8-Math" prog_lang="custom-colors" readonly="False" tags="School" unique_id="10"><rich_text></rich_text></node></node></cherrytree>